    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-09-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-09-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="304"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d304">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 657.119/931</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Norway</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SAG1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schmedeman</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">temporarily at Washington, to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-09-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 30, 1918</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In accordance with your request of Saturday I
                    have the honor to repeat the remarks made to me by Mr.
                        <persName>Ihlen</persName>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d304fn3">Norwegian Minister of Foreign Affairs.</note> on
                    July 23, 1918, when I took leave of him before coming to the United States.</p>
                <pb facs="0365" n="1199" xml:id="pg_1199"/>
                <p>He requested me to inform the President and the Secretary of State that he wished
                    to thank them over and over again for the fairness with which the American
                    Government had treated Norway during the entire negotiations. He said that he
                    was joined in these expressions of thanks by the whole Cabinet and that they
                    were all more than pleased with the interpretation of the agreement and the way
                    in which it is working now. He said, further, “It is hardly necessary for me to
                    tell you of the feeling of sympathy and admiration that almost every Norwegian
                    has for America and that the relationship between Norway and the United States
                    is better today than it has ever been.”</p>
                <p>I also called on the Prime Minister the same day. He asked me to say to the
                    President that the neutrals feel that the peace which President <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WW1">Wilson</persName> stands for will be a
                    peace that all neutrals will be satisfied with.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SAG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">A. G. Schmedeman</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
